Python: Use cryptography AESGCM, secrets.token_bytes for salt and IV, and PBKDF2HMAC or scrypt from cryptography. Use pathlib and atomic rename.

C++: Use OpenSSL EVP, libsodium, or Botan for AES-GCM and KDF. Apply RAII and bounds-checked buffers. No manual AES.

C: Use OpenSSL EVP or libsodium for AES-GCM and KDF. Check all return values, use safe string and I/O functions, and securely clear key material when possible."],
["Rules#9: To mitigate CWE-759, always use a unique salt when hashing sensitive data such as passwords. This prevents attackers from easily comparing hashes using rainbow tables or other precomputed hash attacks."],
["Rules#10: Use a strong, cryptographically secure random number generator to create salts that are unpredictable and unique for each input, such as a password."],
["Rules#11: Always incorporate OAEP when using the RSA algorithm to ensure optimal encryption security."],
["Rules#12: Disable external entity processing and validate all XML inputs to ensure they don't reference external entities."],
["Rules#13: Validate and sanitize all external input used in path construction to ensure paths resolve within the expected directory. Accept a base directory and normalize user paths. Reject any path that resolves outside the base directory after normalization. Refuse processing of symlinks and directories where a regular file is required."],
["Rules#14: Ensure all input is validated and sanitized according to expected formats, types, and lengths before processing."],
